.ie \n(.g .ds Aq \(aq
.el .ds Aq '
.TH pif-config-systems 1  "pif-config-systems " 
.SH NAME
pif\-config\-systems \- Manage the systems filter (restricts Auto mode to specific systems)
.SH SYNOPSIS
\fBpif\-config\-systems\fR [\fB\-h\fR|\fB\-\-help\fR] <\fIsubcommands\fR>
.SH DESCRIPTION
Manage the systems filter (restricts Auto mode to specific systems)
.PP
When \-\-system=auto (the default), pif normally considers all known systems. Adding a systems filter tells Auto mode to behave as if only the listed systems exist — useful when you work with multiple IF systems but want installs scoped to a subset.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\fB\-h\fR, \fB\-\-help\fR
Print help (see a summary with \*(Aq\-h\*(Aq)
.SH SUBCOMMANDS
.TP
pif\-config\-systems\-set(1)
Replace the entire systems filter with a new list
.TP
pif\-config\-systems\-add(1)
Add one or more systems to the existing filter
.TP
pif\-config\-systems\-remove(1)
Remove one or more systems from the filter
.TP
pif\-config\-systems\-reset(1)
Remove the entire systems filter
.TP
pif\-config\-systems\-help(1)
Print this message or the help of the given subcommand(s)
